{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570230"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22882"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.74,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15737"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15737"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94358"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"9885"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"46066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46067"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 51-year-old man undergoes a radical right nephrectomy for a renal cell carcinoma. The surgeon reports an uneventful procedure. A drain is inserted into the operative field. Two days later the patient looks well and has resumed a normal diet. The drain contents are inspected (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dP8CokaLB84p8r3TkzOV28niotcGYN.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately explains the contents of the drain bag?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal post-operative fluid","Leak from the common bile duct","Damage to the cisterna chyli","Perforation of the duodenum","Pus from an abscess"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPost-operative drain output should be interpreted in the context of anatomy disturbed by the operation and the timing relative to diet. After right nephrectomy, lymphatic channels near the right renal hilum, inferior vena cava, and a dilated lymphatic reservoir (cisterna chyli) can be at risk. Chyle is characteristically milky and odourless, and its volume often rises after reintroduction of dietary fat. Recognising this pattern helps differentiate it from bile, enteric contents, and purulent drainage, which have different colours, consistencies, and odours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal post-operative fluid\u003C/strong\u003E is typically serous or serosanguinous, straw-coloured to pink, and does not become opaque and milky with dietary fat. An increasing volume of opaque, milky fluid after resuming oral intake is not consistent with simple post-operative exudate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeak from the common bile duct\u003C/strong\u003E produces bile-stained fluid that is green to dark yellow and often has a distinctive bile odour. A right nephrectomy is distant from the extrahepatic biliary tree, and the described milky white appearance without bile staining is not compatible with a biliary leak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDamage to the cisterna chyli\u003C/strong\u003E best explains the milky, odourless drain output that increases after eating. The cisterna chyli lies anterior to the vertebral bodies around L1\u2013L2, near the right renal vein and inferior vena cava. During radical right nephrectomy, disruption of these lymphatic channels can cause a chyle leak that becomes apparent after dietary fat intake stimulates chyle production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforation of the duodenum\u003C/strong\u003E would usually result in bilious or enteric fluid with particulate matter and a characteristic faeculent or digestive odour, often accompanied by clinical deterioration with pain, tachycardia, fever, and peritonism. The patient appears well, and the fluid is milky rather than bilious or faeculent, making this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPus from an abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is typically thick, purulent, and malodorous, often yellow, green, or brown, and usually associated with systemic features such as fever and localised tenderness. The drain output here is odourless and milky, and the patient is clinically well, arguing against pus. It is unlikely that an abscess would have developed within two days of elective surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Milky, odourless drain output that increases after oral fat intake suggests chyle due to lymphatic injury.","The cisterna chyli lies near the right renal hilum and inferior vena cava, making it vulnerable during right nephrectomy.","Chyle leak typically presents after resumption of diet; bile, enteric contents, and pus have distinct appearances and odours."],"references":["Sarangi SS, Bhirud DP, Sandhu AS, et al. Post-operative chyle leak following nephrectomy: Inference from tertiary care center and review of literature. Urologia. 2024; 91:33-41."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22081"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22081"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dP8CokaLB84p8r3TkzOV28niotcGYN.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dP8CokaLB84p8r3TkzOV28niotcGYN.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94358"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-29T17:02:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-29T18:03:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15737"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78",